Use of this and super Keyword in Java

üí° 1. The this Keyword
‚úÖ Definition:

this is a reference variable in Java that refers to the current object ‚Äî the object whose method or constructor is being invoked.

‚öôÔ∏è Uses of this Keyword
No.	Use	Description	Example
1Ô∏è‚É£	Refers to current instance variables	Helps differentiate between instance variables and parameters with the same name.	this.variable
2Ô∏è‚É£	Calls current class methods	Used when a method calls another method of the same class.	this.methodName()
3Ô∏è‚É£	Calls another constructor (constructor chaining)	Used to call one constructor from another within the same class.	this()
4Ô∏è‚É£	Passes current object as argument	Passes the current object reference to another method or constructor.	method(this)
5Ô∏è‚É£	Returns current object	Useful for method chaining.	return this;
üîπ Example 1: Referring to Instance Variables
class Student {
    String name;
    int age;

    Student(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;  // differentiates instance variable from parameter
        this.age = age;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age);
    }
}

public class ThisExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student("Riya", 21);
        s1.display();
    }
}


Output:

Name: Riya, Age: 21

üîπ Example 2: Calling Another Constructor
class Employee {
    String name;
    int salary;

    Employee() {
        this("Unknown", 0);  // calls parameterized constructor
    }

    Employee(String name, int salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(name + " earns " + salary);
    }
}

public class ConstructorChaining {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new Employee();
        Employee e2 = new Employee("Ankit", 50000);
        e1.display();
        e2.display();
    }
}


Output:

Unknown earns 0
Ankit earns 50000

üîπ Example 3: Returning Current Object
class Demo {
    Demo getDemo() {
        return this;
    }

    void show() {
        System.out.println("Returned current object using this");
    }
}

public class ReturnThis {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Demo().getDemo().show(); // method chaining
    }
}

üß† Summary of this Keyword
Purpose	Example
Refer instance variable	this.variable
Call another constructor	this()
Call current class method	this.method()
Return current object	return this;
Pass as argument	method(this)
üí° 2. The super Keyword
‚úÖ Definition:

super is a reference variable used to refer to the immediate parent class object.

It allows access to:

Parent class variables

Parent class methods

Parent class constructors

‚öôÔ∏è Uses of super Keyword
No.	Use	Description
1Ô∏è‚É£	Access parent class variable	When child and parent have the same variable names.
2Ô∏è‚É£	Access parent class method	To call overridden methods of the parent class.
3Ô∏è‚É£	Call parent class constructor	To invoke parent constructor from subclass constructor.
üîπ Example 1: Accessing Parent Class Variables
class Parent {
    int value = 100;
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int value = 200;

    void show() {
        System.out.println("Child value: " + value);
        System.out.println("Parent value: " + super.value);
    }
}

public class SuperVariable {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child c = new Child();
        c.show();
    }
}


Output:

Child value: 200
Parent value: 100

üîπ Example 2: Calling Parent Class Method
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal is eating...");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Dog is eating...");
    }

    void show() {
        super.eat(); // Calls parent class method
        eat();       // Calls child class method
    }
}

public class SuperMethod {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.show();
    }
}


Output:

Animal is eating...
Dog is eating...

üîπ Example 3: Calling Parent Constructor
class Vehicle {
    Vehicle() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle constructor called");
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    Car() {
        super(); // Calls Vehicle class constructor
        System.out.println("Car constructor called");
    }
}

public class SuperConstructor {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car c = new Car();
    }
}


Output:

Vehicle constructor called
Car constructor called

üßæ Summary Table
Keyword	Refers To	Used For	Example
this	Current class object	Accessing current class members	this.name, this()
super	Parent class object	Accessing parent class members	super.name, super()
‚úÖ Quick Comparison
Feature	this	super
Refers to	Current class instance	Parent class instance
Calls constructor	this() ‚Üí current class constructor	super() ‚Üí parent class constructor
Accesses	Current class members	Parent class members
Inheritance use	No	Yes
